




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Toeholds and Takeovers
AU  - Bulow, Jeremy
AU  - Huang, Ming
AU  - Klemperer, Paul
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250068
DO  - 10.1086/250068
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 427
EP  - 454
VL  - 107
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Toeholds have an enormous impact in ?common?value? takeover battles, such as those between two financial bidders. This contrasts with the small impact of a toehold, in a ?private?value? auction, Our results are consistent with empirical findings that a toehold helps a buyer win an auction, sometimes very cheaply. A controlling minority shareholder may therefore be effectively immune to outside offers. A target may benefit by requiring ?best and final? scaled?bid offers or by selling a cheap toehold or options to a ?white knight,? Our analysis extends to regulators selling ?stranded assets,? creditors bidding in bankruptcy auctions, and so forth.
AB  - Toeholds have an enormous impact in ?common?value? takeover battles, such as those between two financial bidders. This contrasts with the small impact of a toehold, in a ?private?value? auction, Our results are consistent with empirical findings that a toehold helps a buyer win an auction, sometimes very cheaply. A controlling minority shareholder may therefore be effectively immune to outside offers. A target may benefit by requiring ?best and final? scaled?bid offers or by selling a cheap toehold or options to a ?white knight,? Our analysis extends to regulators selling ?stranded assets,? creditors bidding in bankruptcy auctions, and so forth.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250068
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250068
Y2  - 2024/03/23
