TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Rise and Decline of the American Ghetto
AU  - Cutler, David M.
AU  - Glaeser, Edward L.
AU  - Vigdor, Jacob L.
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250069
DO  - 10.1086/250069
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 455
EP  - 506
VL  - 107
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines segregation in American cities from 1890 to 1990. From 1890 to 1940, ghettos were born as blacks migrated to urban areas and cities developed vast expanses filled with almost entirely black housing. From 1940 to 1970, black migration continued and the physical areas of the ghettos expanded. Since 1970, there has been a decline in segregation as blacks have moved into previously all?white areas of cities and suburbs. Across all these time periods there is a strong positive relation between urban population or density and segregation. Data on house prices and attitudes toward integration suggest that in the mid?twentieth century, segregation was a product of collective actions taken by whites to exclude blacks from their neighborhoods. By 1990, the legal barriers enforcing segregation had been replaced by decentralized racism, where whites pay more than blacks to live in predominantly white areas.
AB  - This paper examines segregation in American cities from 1890 to 1990. From 1890 to 1940, ghettos were born as blacks migrated to urban areas and cities developed vast expanses filled with almost entirely black housing. From 1940 to 1970, black migration continued and the physical areas of the ghettos expanded. Since 1970, there has been a decline in segregation as blacks have moved into previously all?white areas of cities and suburbs. Across all these time periods there is a strong positive relation between urban population or density and segregation. Data on house prices and attitudes toward integration suggest that in the mid?twentieth century, segregation was a product of collective actions taken by whites to exclude blacks from their neighborhoods. By 1990, the legal barriers enforcing segregation had been replaced by decentralized racism, where whites pay more than blacks to live in predominantly white areas.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250069
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250069
Y2  - 2024/03/23
